==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Throng
<hw>Throng</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧rong</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧rang</ets>, AS.
<ets>ge⟦thorn⟧rang</ets>, fr. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ringan</ets> to crowd, to
press; akin to OS. <ets>thringan</ets>, D. & G. <ets>dringen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>dringan</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ryngva</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧r⟦oum⟧ngva</ets>, Goth. <ets>⟦thorn⟧riehan</ets>, D. & G.
<ets>drang</ets> a throng, press, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧r⟦oum⟧ng</ets> a
throng, Lith. <ets>trenkti</ets> to jolt, <ets>tranksmas</ets> a tumult.
Cf. <er>Thring</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A multitude of persons or
of living beings pressing or pressed into a close body or assemblage; a
crowd.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A great multitude; <as>as, the heavenly
<ex>throng</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Throng</er>, <er>Multitude</er>,
<er>Crowd</er>.</syn> <usage> Any great number of persons form a
<xex>multitude</xex>; a <xex>throng</xex> is a large number of persons
who are gathered or are moving together in a collective body; a
<xex>crowd</xex> is composed of a large or small number of persons who
press together so as to bring their bodies into immediate or
inconvenient contact. A dispersed <xex>multitude</xex>; the
<xex>throngs</xex> in the streets of a city; the <xex>crowd</xex> at a
fair or a street fight. But these distinctions are not carefully
observed.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So, with this bold opposer rushes on⟦br⟧
This many-headed monster, <qex>multitude</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not to know me argues yourselves unknown,⟦br⟧
The lowest of your <qex>throng</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I come from empty noise, and tasteless pomp,⟦br⟧
From <qex>crowds</qex> that hide a monarch from himself.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Throng</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Throng
<hw>Throng</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Thronged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Thronging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To crowd together; to press
together into a close body, as a multitude of persons; to gather or move
in multitudes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have seen the dumb men <qex>throng</qex> to see him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Throng</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Throng
<hw>Throng</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To crowd, or press,
as persons; to oppress or annoy with a crowd of living beings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Much people followed him, and <qex>thronged</qex> him.</q>
<rj><qau>Mark v. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To crowd into; to fill closely by crowding or
pressing into, as a hall or a street.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Throng</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Throng
<hw>Throng</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Thronged; crowded; also, much
occupied; busy.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp.
Sanderson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the intent the sick . . . should not lie too
<qex>throng</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson (More's Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Throngly</ent>⟦br⟧
